Name: Economist Dollar Metals Price Index
Metadata: The index is currently calculated in U.S. Dollars, Pounds Sterling and SDRs.  The dollar index is used here beginning in 1971; all previous data are in pounds sterling. The Economist Price Index has been calculated since 1851.  The index was calculated infrequently during the 1850s, semi-annually beginning in 1860, and monthly beginning in 1900.  The data from 1851 through 1910 can be found in the issue of March 26, 1938, p. 725. The first index was calculated through 1928 using a base of 1901-1905 with different bases for each sector.  More information on this index can be obtained from the issue of February 4, 1911, pp. 206-207.  These indices were republished in the issues of April 2, 1938, p. 66 and April 9, 1938, p. 126.  A new index was introduced in 1928 for which the issue of December 15, 1928, p. 197 should be consulted.  These data were republished in the issues of April-June 1938, pp. 282, 461, 522. The annual Commercial History and Review issues published annual summaries of the data each year. A new series of data was published in the issue of July 7, 1973, pp. 70-71 which extended these series back to 1949. In the March 2, 1974 issue, the index was revised to provide prices in both dollars and in pounds. For more information on the indices, see issues of The Economist from December 15, 1928 (p. 197), July 19, 1952 (p. 182), January 7, 1961 (p. 59), May 6, 1967 (p. 593), July 7, 1973 (pp. 70-71), and March 2, 1974 (pp. 86-87).  In 1974, the index was weighted between food (55.6%), fibers (13.8%), metals (24.2%) and miscellaneous (7.4%). We provide three sets of data from the Economist Indicators: the original series from 1851-1928 (For purposes of comparison, the index of commodity prices calculated by Rostow has been included for the period 1800 through 1850 to lengthen the series.  These data were taken from W. W. Rostow and Anna J. Schwartz, The Growth and Fluctuation of the British Economy 1790-1850), (2 vols.), Oxford: Oxford U.P., 1953). The second series goes from 1924 to 1952. The current Economist series have these historical series appended onto them to create a single long-term series, and they use the first series through 1923, the second series through 1948, and the third series through 1969.  All the data through 1969 are in pounds sterling, and the current series, which begin in 1970, use dollar prices rather than the pound sterling.   The index was revised in 2005 with the index base changed to 2000 = 100.  The indices were weighted according to the value of world imports in 1999-2001 with the EU counting as a single market. The weighting was Foods 56.4% (Wheat 14.6%, coffee 12.8%, soyabeans 11.8%, maize 9.6%, soyameal 8.3%, rice 6.9%, sugar 6.6%, beef (American) 5.8%, beef (Australian) 5.8%, cocoa 5.3%, palm oil 4.1%, soyaoil 3.%, tea 2.9%, lamb 1.9% and cocnut oil 0.5%), Industrials 43.6% of which Metals 28.2% (Aluminum 49.7%, copper 27.9%, Nickel 9.3%, Zinc 7.9%, Lead 2.6%, Tin 2.6%) and Non-food Agricultural Commodities 15.4% (Cotton 32.6%, Rubber 18.8%, timber 17.1%, Hides 11.2%, Australian Wool 6.8%, New Zealand Wool 6.8%, Palm Oil 3.8%, Coconut oil 2.2% and soyaoil 0.6%).The index was revised again in 2010 with the index base changed to 2005 = 100 with the weights changed as follows:Aluminium	42.2Copper	34.6Nickel	10.9Zinc	6.6Tin	3.2Lead	2.4
